body:
I absolutely do have the exact same problem.  When a blank field is submitted and the form repopulates, the default value is used by `set_value()` instead of a blank field.  Described in greater detail, and referred to this GitHub page from here...

http://forum.codeigniter.com/thread-61600-post-317554.html#pid317554

---

**EDIT**:

I was setting up a test page and discovered that this **fix does not work when the name of the field is part of an indexed array**, like `name[1]`, etc.

**DEMO**:  < removed live demo >

View:

```
<?php echo form_open(current_url()) ?>

    <?php $first = isset($first) ? $first : ''; ?>
    first: <input type="text" name="first" value="<?php echo set_value('first', $first); ?>" />
    <?php echo (form_error('first') ? form_error('first') : ''); ?>

    <?php $name['1'] = isset($name['1']) ? $name['1'] : ''; ?>
    name[1]: <input type="text" name="name[1]" value="<?php echo set_value('name[1]', $name['1']); ?>" />
    <?php echo (form_error('name[1]') ? form_error('name[1]') : ''); ?>

    <input type="submit" />

</form>
```

Controller:

```
$data['first'] = "12345";
$data['name']['1'] = "12345";

$this->load->library('form_validation');
$this->form_validation->set_rules('first', 'first', 'required|numeric');
$this->form_validation->set_rules('name[1]', 'Name 1', 'required|numeric');

if ($this->form_validation->run() === TRUE)
{
    // passed validation    
}

$this->load->view('setvaluebug', $data);
```

@rierei That doesn't necessarily mean that it supports @sparky672's case.

@sparky672 Would it really make sense to you if 'foo' and 'foo[1]' were the same thing? They aren't ... In fact, it was a bug that they were the same thing to CI2.

'foo[bar]' and 'foo[]' should work fine, but 'foo[1]' is ... Let's just say that there's no way to make it work properly without breaking something else.

issue.body:
Using set_value('field_name', 'default value') on a form field. If you delete the value and submit the form, the form_validation (set to required) correctly flags the field_name, however the value is incorrectly pre-populated with the default value.

Line 446 in system/libraries/Form_validation.php contains the following;

```
elseif (isset($validation_array[$field]) && $validation_array[$field] !== '') {
    $this->_field_data[$field]['postdata'] = $validation_array[$field];
}
```

This checks the data (defaults to $_POST), however because the data is an empty string, it doesn't populate the postdata. The form_helper function and form_validation method `set_value()` reverts back to the default value if the postdata is empty, thus showing the incorrect data in the form.
